The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

 The City Diary

 A division bench of Calcutta High Court, comprising Justice A. Kabir and Justice K. Bishi, on Wednesday directed the Calcutta Metropolitan Development Authority, public works department, Calcutta Municipal Corporation, Calcutta Port Trust and the Calcutta Tramways Company to file affidavits stating the progress in maintenance work on city roads.

 month ago, the court had taken exception to the failure of the agencies and the civic body in repairing the roads. The bench asked them to take all possible measures to improve the condition of roads. The order was passed on a public interest litigation moved by Idris Ali and others, seeking directions to the authorities concerned for immediate repair of city roads. 

 A city court on Wednesday took up a petition challenging the description of Amartya Sen as a Nobel laureate in a translated work of the economist, and directed the respondents to appear before it on January 20, 2005. Petitioner Subodh Chandra Roy contended that Sen had not been awarded a Nobel prize and filed a case of cheating and conspiracy against the publisher, translator and the cover designer of the book Unnayan-o-Swakhamata. Sen is not among the respondents. 

 oy, a doctorate in nuclear physics, challenged the description ?arthanititey Nobel puroshkar prapto? (Nobel laureate in economics) on the cover of the book. He held that Nobel prizes are awarded in physics, chemistry, physiology or medicine, literature and peace. The Bank of Sweden had instituted a prize in economic sciences in 1968 in the memory of Alfred Nobel. Sen was awarded this prize in 1998, Roy argued.

 A Calcutta High Court bench of Justice Pratap Kumar Roy and Justice Jyotirmoy Bhattacharya will hear on Thursday a petition challenging the Trinamul Congress? decision to call a Bangla bandh on December 3. 

 Following Mamata Banerjee?s suggestion, mayor Subrata Mukherjee has decided to institute annual departmental rewards for the best employees. The awards will be in the form of a special increment.

 Air-India will introduce an additional pair of flights on the Mumbai-Calcutta-Mumbai route from December 2. The flights, to be operated on Thursdays, will leave Mumbai at 1.20 am and will reach Calcutta at 3.35 am. The return flights will leave at 4.30 am and will reach Mumbai at 7.15 am. An airline release said the flights will have convenient international connections to and from Mumbai.

 A 28-year-old undertrial prisoner attempted suicide on Thursday morning in the toilet of Bankshall court. Police said the incident took place around 11 am, when Rahim Khan was brought to court from Presidency jail. He was taken to SSKM Hospital.

 The outgoing country head of Britain?s Department For International Development in India, Charlotte Seymore-Smith, called on chief minister Buddhadeb Bhattacharjee at Writers Buildings on Wednesday evening. 

 The Airports Authority of India and the Central Industrial Security Force released a passenger feedback form at NSC Bose International Airport on Wednesday morning.

 Transport minister Subhas Chakraborty on Wednesday called for a 30-minute chakka jam from noon on December 1 to protest the hike in fuel prices. 

 The All Bengal Electricity Consumers? Association has called for a 30-minute ?blackout? on Thursday evening, demanding withdrawal of the hike in power tariff and arrears. 

